<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="reference_group">
<paragraph lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus, 1753" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Microteaceae" genus="Galenia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Galenia celosioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="celosioides">Galenia celosioides</taxonomicName>
Spreng., Nov. Prov.: 18 (1818). ≡ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Link" authorityYear="1821" baseAuthorityName="Spreng." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Microteaceae" genus="Aphananthe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aphananthe celosioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="celosioides">Aphananthe celosioides</taxonomicName>
(Spreng.) Link, Enum. Hort. Berol. Alt. 1: 383 (1821). Neotype (designated here by Sennikov &amp; Sukhorukov): BRAZIL. Bahia, Mucuri, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="März">Maerz</normalizedToken>
[March] 1816, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Maximilian, Prinz zu Wied 53</emphasis>
(BR0000005575398! Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Neotype of Galenia celosioides (BR 0000005575398)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.115.29041.figure14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/255667" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">14</figureCitation>
). Notes. Although 
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus, 1753" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Microteaceae" genus="Galenia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Galenia celosioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="celosioides">Galenia celosioides</taxonomicName>
was synonymized with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Microteaceae" genus="Microtea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Microtea maypurensis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="maypurensis">Microtea maypurensis</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Moquin-Tandon, A" editor="De Candolle, A" journalOrPublisher="13, pt. 2. V. Masson, Paris" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="3 - 40" refId="B34" refString="Moquin-Tandon, A, 1849. Phytolaccaceae. In: De Candolle, A, Ed., Prodromus systematis universalis regni vegetabilis, Vol. 13, pt. 2. V. Masson, Paris: 3 - 40" title="Phytolaccaceae." volumeTitle="Prodromus systematis universalis regni vegetabilis, Vol." year="1849">Moquin-Tandon 1849</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmidt, JA" editor="Martius, KFP" journalOrPublisher="14, pt. 2. Fleischner, Leipzig" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="326 - 344" refId="B41" refString="Schmidt, JA, 1872. Phytolaccaceae. In: Martius, KFP, Hooker, JD, Eichler, AG, Engler, A, Baker, JG, Rohrbach, P, Schmidt, JA, Eds., Flora Brasiliensis, Vol. 14, pt. 2. Fleischner, Leipzig: 326 - 344" title="Phytolaccaceae." volumeTitle="Flora Brasiliensis, Vol." year="1872">
<pageBreakToken pageId="18" pageNumber="19" start="start">Schmidt</pageBreakToken>
1872
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Walter, H" journalOrPublisher="Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie (Beiblatt)" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" refId="B61" refString="Walter, H, 1909. Phytolaccaceae. In: Engler A (Ed.) Das Pflanzenreich, Heft 39. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig." title="Phytolaccaceae. In: Engler A (Ed.) Das Pflanzenreich, Heft 39. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig." year="1909">Walter 1909</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2395128" author="Nowicke, WH" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="294 - 364" refId="B37" refString="Nowicke, WH, 1968. Palynotaxonomic study of the Phytolaccaceae. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 55 (3): 294 - 364, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2395128" title="Palynotaxonomic study of the Phytolaccaceae." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2395128" volume="55" year="1968">Nowicke 1968</bibRefCitation>
) or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sw., Prodr. [O. P. Swartz]: 53" authorityYear="1788" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. debilis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="debilis">M. debilis</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Steudel, ET" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" refId="B48" refString="Steudel, ET, 1841. Nomenclator botanicus seu synonymia plantarum universalis, Vol. 2. J.G. Cottae, Stuttgart &amp; Tuebingen." title="Nomenclator botanicus seu synonymia plantarum universalis, Vol. 2. J. G. Cottae, Stuttgart &amp; Tuebingen." year="1841">Steudel 1841</bibRefCitation>
), the protologue (
<bibRefCitation author="Sprengel, K" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" refId="B44" refString="Sprengel, K, 1818. Novi proventus hortorum academicorum Halensis et Berolinensis. Gebauer, Halle." title="Novi proventus hortorum academicorum Halensis et Berolinensis. Gebauer, Halle." year="1818">Sprengel 1818</bibRefCitation>
) contains the phrases &quot;flosculi 
<normalizedToken originalValue="…">...</normalizedToken>
brevissime pedicellati
<normalizedToken originalValue="…">...</normalizedToken>
styli duo&quot; [flowers very shortly pedicellate, styles two], the characters found in 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. celosioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="celosioides">M. celosioides</taxonomicName>
. The description did not include reference to the presence of hooked outgrowths, a peculiar feature of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="G. Don, Hort. Brit. [Loudon]: 98" authorityYear="1830" baseAuthorityName="Kunth" family="Microteaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. maypurensis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="maypurensis">M. maypurensis</taxonomicName>
, and the short pedicels and two styles also exclude this species. Nevertheless, 
<bibRefCitation author="Moquin-Tandon, A" editor="De Candolle, A" journalOrPublisher="13, pt. 2. V. Masson, Paris" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="3 - 40" refId="B34" refString="Moquin-Tandon, A, 1849. Phytolaccaceae. In: De Candolle, A, Ed., Prodromus systematis universalis regni vegetabilis, Vol. 13, pt. 2. V. Masson, Paris: 3 - 40" title="Phytolaccaceae." volumeTitle="Prodromus systematis universalis regni vegetabilis, Vol." year="1849">Moquin-Tandon (1849)</bibRefCitation>
reported his former intention to transfer 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sprengel’s">Sprengel's</normalizedToken>
name to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Microteaceae" genus="Microtea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Microtea" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Microtea</taxonomicName>
, apparently on the basis of his analysis of its protologue. He changed his mind probably because he did not examine the original material of the name. 
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus, 1753" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Microteaceae" genus="Galenia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Galenia celosioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="celosioides">Galenia celosioides</taxonomicName>
was introduced anonymously to the Berlin Botanical Garden, from which it was described as new to science by the end of 1818 (
<bibRefCitation author="Sprengel, K" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" refId="B44" refString="Sprengel, K, 1818. Novi proventus hortorum academicorum Halensis et Berolinensis. Gebauer, Halle." title="Novi proventus hortorum academicorum Halensis et Berolinensis. Gebauer, Halle." year="1818">Sprengel 1818</bibRefCitation>
). Although the source of introduction was not recorded, among European plant collectors in Brazil it was only Alexander Philipp Maximilian, Prince of Wied-Neuwied (1782-1867), who collected specimens early enough to bring the material to Berlin before the protologue of 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="G." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="G. celosioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="celosioides">G. celosioides</taxonomicName>
had been published. Prince Maximilian travelled in Brazil during 1815-1817, in the States of Rio de Janeiro, Bahia and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Espírito">Espirito</normalizedToken>
Santo, mostly along the coast. He left for Europe in May 1817 and arrived at Lisbon on 1st July. Very shortly after the arrival he started to distribute dried specimens, seeds and even living collections which he donated to botanical experts and gardens in Germany and Belgium. Large amounts of seeds were sent to Ghent, Antwerp and Enghien, but it is unknown which seeds were sent to Germany (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.13102/neod.42.1" author="Moraes, PLR" journalOrPublisher="Neodiversity" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="16 - 51" refId="B35" refString="Moraes, PLR, 2009. The Brazilian herbarium of Maximilian. Prince of Wied. Neodiversity 4 (2): 16 - 51, DOI: https://doi.org/10.13102/neod.42.1" title="The Brazilian herbarium of Maximilian. Prince of Wied." url="https://doi.org/10.13102/neod.42.1" volume="4" year="2009">Moraes 2009</bibRefCitation>
). A herbarium voucher of 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. paniculata" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="paniculata">M. paniculata</taxonomicName>
numbered 53 by C.G.D. Nees von Esenbeck, a German botanist who received a large set of specimens from Prince Maximilian for collaborative work, can be found in the Nees herbarium at BR. This number was cited by 
<bibRefCitation author="Walter, H" journalOrPublisher="Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie (Beiblatt)" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" refId="B61" refString="Walter, H, 1909. Phytolaccaceae. In: Engler A (Ed.) Das Pflanzenreich, Heft 39. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig." title="Phytolaccaceae. In: Engler A (Ed.) Das Pflanzenreich, Heft 39. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig." year="1909">Walter (1909)</bibRefCitation>
as referable to 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. paniculata" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="paniculata">M. paniculata</taxonomicName>
(specimen destroyed at B). Along with the characters stated in the protologue of 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="G." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="G. celosioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="celosioides">G. celosioides</taxonomicName>
, this fact provides indirect evidence that Prince 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Maximilian’s">Maximilian's</normalizedToken>
collections were the likely source of the introduction of 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="G." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="G. celosioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="celosioides">G. celosioides</taxonomicName>
to the Botanical Garden in Berlin. There are no specimens of the original material of 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="G." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="G. celosioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="celosioides">G. celosioides</taxonomicName>
in existence, which probably was acquired by B and then destroyed (
<bibRefCitation author="Stafleu, FA" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" refId="B46" refString="Stafleu, FA, Cowan, RS, 1985. Taxonomic literature. A selective guide to botanical publications and collections with dates, commentaries and types, Vol. 5. Bohn, Scheltema &amp; Holkema, Utrecht &amp; Antwerpen; dr. W. Junk b.v., Publishers, The Hague &amp; Boston. Regnum Vegetabile: 112." title="Taxonomic literature. A selective guide to botanical publications and collections with dates, commentaries and types, Vol. 5. Bohn, Scheltema &amp; Holkema, Utrecht &amp; Antwerpen; dr. W. Junk b. v., Publishers, The Hague &amp; Boston. Regnum Vegetabile: 112." year="1985">Stafleu and Cowan 1985</bibRefCitation>
). Since the characters of the Prince 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Maximilian’s">Maximilian's</normalizedToken>
specimen at BR are in good agreement with the protologue of 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="G." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="G. celosioides" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="celosioides">G. celosioides</taxonomicName>
, we designate this specimen as a neotype of the species name. This name is therefore the earliest one available for the species also known as 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. paniculata" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="paniculata">M. paniculata</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. paniculata" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="paniculata">M. paniculata</taxonomicName>
Moq. in DC., Prodr. 13(2): 18 (1849), 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">syn. nov.</emphasis>
Lectotype (designated by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2395128" author="Nowicke, WH" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="294 - 364" refId="B37" refString="Nowicke, WH, 1968. Palynotaxonomic study of the Phytolaccaceae. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 55 (3): 294 - 364, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2395128" title="Palynotaxonomic study of the Phytolaccaceae." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2395128" volume="55" year="1968">Nowicke 1968</bibRefCitation>
: 350): BRAZIL. Bahia, &quot;Serra Jacobina&quot; [Villa do Barra, according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Moquin-Tandon, A" editor="De Candolle, A" journalOrPublisher="13, pt. 2. V. Masson, Paris" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="3 - 40" refId="B34" refString="Moquin-Tandon, A, 1849. Phytolaccaceae. In: De Candolle, A, Ed., Prodromus systematis universalis regni vegetabilis, Vol. 13, pt. 2. V. Masson, Paris: 3 - 40" title="Phytolaccaceae." volumeTitle="Prodromus systematis universalis regni vegetabilis, Vol." year="1849">Moquin-Tandon (1849)</bibRefCitation>
], [1837], Blanchet 2709 (K000601204! isolectotype P00743956!).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. longebracteata" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="longebracteata">M. longebracteata</taxonomicName>
H.Walter, Pflanzenr. (Engler) 39: 129 (1909), 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">syn. nov</emphasis>
. Lectotype (Sennikov &amp; Sukhorukov, designated here): BRAZIL. Prov. Bahia, zwischen den Campos und Vittoria, [1815], 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Sellow 359</emphasis>
(B 10 0250568! isolectotypes - B 10 0250569! B 10 0250570!). Note: The main character distinguishing 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. longebracteata" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="longebracteata">M. longebracteata</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName family="Microteaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. paniculata" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="paniculata">M. paniculata</taxonomicName>
is the length of the bracts that is equal to those of the flowers (
<bibRefCitation author="Walter, H" journalOrPublisher="Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie (Beiblatt)" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" refId="B61" refString="Walter, H, 1909. Phytolaccaceae. In: Engler A (Ed.) Das Pflanzenreich, Heft 39. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig." title="Phytolaccaceae. In: Engler A (Ed.) Das Pflanzenreich, Heft 39. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig." year="1909">Walter 1909</bibRefCitation>
). However, the length of the bracts in both taxa is equal to that of the flower buds, and the length of fully opened flowers is greater than the length of the subtending bract.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Annuals or biennials; stems erect, up to 100 cm; leaves petiolate (petioles up to 2.0 cm), blades 3.0-10.0(12.0) cm long, 0.2-2.0 cm wide, cuneate, lanceolate to oblong, rarely ovate, glabrous or their margins and mid-rib below covered with papillae; inflorescence a spike, long and spreading, whip-like; flowers with a bract and two filiform bracteoles (often not well-visible), bracts longer than flowers at the beginning, then equal to the perianth segments; pedicels up to 1.0 mm at fruiting, perianth segments 5, oblong or ovoid; stamens 5-8; stigmas 2, thick; fruit with scattered short outgrowths, fruit body (1.0)1.1-1.4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.9-1.1 mm, 1.5-2 times as long as the perianth (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Fruits and seeds of Microtea debilis and M. celosioides: A, B fruit of M. debilis, enclosed in the perianth (St. Lucia, Soufriere, 1958, G. R. Proctor 17789, BM 000019256) C, D seed of M. debilis (Honduras, nr Cangrejal river, foothills of Ceiba, 29 Jul 1938, T. G. Yuncker et al. 8674, G) E, F fruit of M. celosioides (Retiro das Pedras, Brumadinho, 14 Dec 1998, J. R. Stehmann &amp; C. E. S. Ferreira 2399, PACA) G, H seed of M. celosioides (Retiro das Pedras, Brumadinho, 14 Dec 1998, J. R. Stehmann &amp; C. E. S. Ferreira 2399, PACA). Magnification: A, E - 30 x, B, F - 100 x, C, G - 50 x, D, H - 300 x." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.115.29041.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/255657" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">4E, F</figureCitation>
); pericarp readily scraped off the seed; seed ~1.0 mm, with rough surface (Fig. 
